<HEADLINE>
<P>
CURRENT PAPERBACKS: THE OXFORD BOOK OF BRITISH POLITICAL ANECDOTES EDITED BY 
PAUL JOHNSON (OXFORD UNIVERSITY PRESS: $8.95) 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By CHARLES SOLOMON 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A rich compendium of stories, bons mots, scandals, etc., from the time of 
Richard III to Harold Wilson, guaranteed to delight trivia buffs. Americans 
unfamiliar with the intricacies of the British party system and its politics 
may miss the point of a few stories, but most of them can be enjoyed by the 
general reader. Many of these anecdotes suggest that Parliamentary debates are 
far more entertaining and literate than the deliberations of the U.S. Congress. 
In 1581, when the House of Commons "had sat long and done in effect nothing," 
the Speaker, Mr. Popham, was asked by Queen Elizabeth I, "Now, Mr. Speaker, 
what hath passed in the Lower House?" He replied, "If it pleases Your Majesty, 
seven weeks." 
</P>
</TEXT>
