<HEADLINE>
<P>
CURRENT PAPERBACKS: THE SACRED PIPE BLACK ELK'S ACCOUNT OF THE SEVEN RITES OF 
THE OGLALA SIOUX RECORDED AND EDITED BY JOSEPH BROWN (UNIVERSITY OF OKLAHOMA 
PRESS: $7.95, ILLUSTRATED) 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By CHARLES SOLOMON 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Black Elk, the Sioux holy man, explains the enormous importance his people 
attached to what is commonly called "the peace pipe." The Sioux believed that 
their ritual pipe was a gift from Wakan-Tanka, the Great Spirit, presented by 
his intermediary, the White Buffalo Cow Woman. Its sacred origins made it an 
essential element in tribal ceremonies involving the purification of the soul, 
relations with the dead and preparations for entering womanhood. These rituals 
focused on the relationships that linked humanity, the Earth, its other 
inhabitants and the all-embracing Great Spirit. At a time when people are 
realizing that they may have irrevocably damaged the planet, the Sioux 
veneration of the Earth seems a worthwhile subject for contemplation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column; Book Review 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA101589-0013 </DOCNO>
