<TEXT>
<P>
FICTION 
</P>
<P>
PALM LATITUDES by Kate Braverman (Penguin: $8.95). The fateful existence of 
three Latina women in a Los Angeles barrio. 
</P>
<P>
HEAVEN'S PRISONER by James Lee Burke (Pocket: $3.99). A plane crash in 
Louisiana thrusts Vietnam vet, ex-detective, ex-drinker Dave Robicheaux into an 
unwanted morass. 
</P>
<P>
GREEN CITY IN THE SUN by Barbara Wood (Fawcett Gold Medal: $4.95). Dr. Deborah 
Treverton is summoned back to Africa to settle the family coffee business -- 
and a medicine woman's curse. 
</P>
<P>
STORIES IN AN ALMOST CLASSICAL MODE by Harold Brodkey (Vintage: $12.95). 
Eighteen stories written over 30 years about the contradictions within 
families. 
</P>
<P>
WHEN I AM AN OLD WOMAN I SHALL WEAR PURPLE: An Anthology of Short Stories and 
Poetry, edited by Sandra Martz (Papier-Mache Press: $10). Writings about the 
later seasons in a woman's life by daughters, sons and significant others. 
</P>
<P>
NONFICTION 
</P>
<P>
CHILD STAR: An Autobiography by Shirley Temple Black (Warner: $5.95). Once 
America's tiniest star, Black reflects on her gigantic impact. 
</P>
<P>
DEADLY MEDICINE by Kelly Moore and Dan Reed (St. Martin's: $4.95). Genene Jones 
seemed to be the perfect nurse, always there in an emergency -- until she was 
convicted of 30 cases of infanticide. 
</P>
<P>
BROTHERS: Black and Poor -- A True Story of Courage and Survival by Sylvester 
Monroe and Peter Goldman (Ballantine: $4.95.) Newsweek correspondent returns to 
his childhood home, Chicago's Taylor Court projects, and discovers a microcosm 
of the plight of black men in America. 
</P>
<P>
THE CLUSTERING OF AMERICA by Michael J. Weiss (Perennial: $10.95). You are not 
where you live, but your zip code can reveal a lot about you. 
</P>
<P>
SELF-HELP / REFERENCETHE OLD FARMER'S 1989 ALMANAC by Robert B. Thomas (Old 
Farmer's Almanac: $2.95) Since 1792, this little book has presented an eclectic 
mix of planting tables, weather forecasts, recipes and astrological secrets. 
</P>
<P>
LIFE AFTER THE CITY: A Harrow-smith Guide to Rural Living by Charles Long 
(Camden House: $12.95). Ruminating chapters on earning a living, transition 
strategies, social adjustments, and maintaining friendships. 
</P>
<P>
VERY LA: The Native's Guide to the Best of Los Angeles by David Hoffman 
(Chronicle: $9.95). If you decide to stay, here's how to make the experience a 
little more enjoyable. 
</P>
