</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
103 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
'SEX' AND ART 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
O'Neill displays shortsightedness when, in his assessment of "sex," he mistakes 
a laconic style for shallowness. He refuses to believe that this "yuppie soap 
opera" could reveal the emptiness of modern life. (A stronger argument might 
have been that the use of yuppies to depict emptiness was too easy.) 
</P>
<P>
O'Neill obviously has definite ideas about what constitutes a work of art, and 
anything that does not conform to those preconceived notions doesn't deserve 
further consideration. This is so much easier than trying to approach a work on 
its own terms. But that would require thought. 
</P>
<P>
MICHAEL BALLARD 
</P>
<P>
Long Beach 
</P>
