<HEADLINE>
<P>
BROTHERLY HELP 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In Patrick Goldstein's Oct. 8 article, actor Beau Bridges is quoted as saying 
that years ago he was afraid his younger brother Jeff "was a pansy," so he took 
him out to the park and taught him to throw a curve ball. 
</P>
<P>
Bridges' comment prompts the following open letter: 
</P>
<P>
Beau, my nephew wanted to go see you and Jeff in your new movie, "The Fabulous 
Baker Boys." You'll be proud of the fact that I told him: 
</P>
<P>
"No way -- you get out there and play some baseball or I'll think you're a 
pansy." 
</P>
<P>
Thanks, Beau. You've saved your brother from a fate worse than death, and now 
my nephew is saved too! 
</P>
<P>
By the way, do all of the young people in your performing-arts group have to 
prove they're straight to work with you? 
</P>
<P>
Or do you just call them "pansy" or "dyke" if they're not? 
</P>
<P>
Do you send them out to toss a few balls around if you're suspicious? 
</P>
<P>
Patrick Goldstein should not have included your remark in his story and The 
Times should not have printed it. 
</P>
<P>
I don't think they did you a favor, and it shows an editorial lack of 
sensitivity. 
</P>
<P>
FRANC CAGGIANO 
</P>
<P>
Malibu 
</P>
</TEXT>
