<HEADLINE>
<P>
NATION: IN BRIEF; 
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON, D. C. ; 
</P>
<P>
SATELLITES CALLED KEY TO FIGHT ON FAMINE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times staff and wire reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Satellite-gathered data on weather, crops and environmental damage will be 
crucial in avoiding world famine in the 21st Century, an Ohio lawmaker said in 
urging support for U.S. Earth-observation programs. Rep. Tony P. Hall (D-Ohio) 
said satellites "are basic tools for humanity in the search for solutions to 
hunger." But according to a report, funding for the primary U.S. satellite 
program, Landsat, is in doubt. Hall, chairman of the House Select Committee on 
Hunger, said the study, "Satellite Technology and World Food Security," offers 
"clear evidence that any loss of our satellite capability will directly affect 
our ability to avert famine." 
</P>
</TEXT>
