<HEADLINE>
<P>
CALIFORNIA: IN BRIEF; 
</P>
<P>
SACRAMENTO; 
</P>
<P>
DETECTIVE ACCUSED OF OBSTRUCTING JUSTICE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A woman detective with the Sacramento Police Department has been charged with 
illegally using police computers to help her body-builder boyfriend in a 
steroid sales scheme. Vicki Romani, 31, who has been released on bail, is 
charged with conspiring with William Cambra to unlawfully use the police 
computer and with obstructing justice. Cambra, a former "Mr. California" and 
owner of a health club, was arrested last month on charges of conspiracy, 
possession and sales of anabolic steroids. He pleaded not guilty in U.S. 
District Court in San Diego last week. Authorities accuse Romani of running 
vehicle license checks for Cambra on the police computer to screen possible 
undercover agents investigating his activities. If convicted, Romani could face 
up to five years in state prison. 
</P>
</TEXT>
